<font color="#FF0000">RIVER OF LIFE</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 20  0:56:01 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
©1997, John C. Ratliff<br><br>
A father asked his boys to meet him down at the river with two buckets full of water balloons.  The father was in his canoe when the two teenage boys finished the task of filling the balloons to his specifications, and met him at the river.  He had asked that most be filled partially with water, and partially with air.  But a couple balloons should be completely filled with water, and a couple completely with air.<br><br>
The boys took their positions in the canoe’s bow and stern, while the father maintained his position in the center section.  They paddled out to the edge of the current, and the father told the boys to dump the balloons into the water, which they did.  <br><br>
Then the father asked them to observe the balloons.  What was happening to them?  Where were they going?  What forces were upon the balloons.<br><br>
The oldest, who’s interest is in physics, noted that the balloons with air were affected by the wind, while the balloons with water were affected by the water’s current.  Those with a mixture were affected by both, depending upon how much air/water they contained.<br><br>
Almost immediately the balloons separated, and the wind carried the mostly air-filled balloons to shore, where they languished in the shallows amongst the brush.  The mostly water-filled balloons tended to follow the canoe’s wake as they paddled away for a distance, then followed the river currents.  The completely water-filled balloon followed the river currents.<br><br>
The father asked the boys what they thought about what they had witnessed?  They replied that the balloons were affected more by what they were mostly filled with.  If they were filled more with air than water, then the winds would blow them more than the river currents would carry them.  The opposite was also true, and if they had more water than air, the river would have more influence.<br><br>
The father then told the boys, “I have not talked much with you about religion, or faith.  But think of this, the world is made of opposites.  All the worlds religions acknowledge this.  The Chinese have the Ying and the Yang, the Lakota have the White Wolf and the Black Wolf, and the Christian world has God and the Devil, good and evil, Love and hate.  <br><br>
“The river’s water represents Love, while the air represents sin.  The balloons are people, and the amounts of water and air inside the balloons represent the Love and sin found in each person.  Notice that all balloons have some of each, as it is not possible to fill a water balloon completely with water.  Some air is trapped inside.<br><br>
“Those balloons filled mostly with air are subject to the winds which blow over the river of life.  They will go whatever way the wind blows, and the wind changes daily.  Sometimes, there is not much wind, and the balloons seem to stay in place.  Sometimes, the wind blows strongly and at cross-purposes to the water’s current.  Then the balloon winds up mired along the shore.  <br><br>
The father then asked that the canoe head for some balloons mired on shore.  When one was alongside the canoe, he took out a pin and punctured the balloon.  The younger boy in the canoe’s bow jumped as the balloon exploded.  The father then asked, “What is left?”  The older boy replied that only fragments of the rubber balloon were left.  The father then asked, “What has this balloon contributed to the river’s water?”  They both replied that very little water was contributed to the river.  In like manner, they collected the rest of the balloons, and the boys delighted in popping them with their paddles.  <br><br>
Then they went looking for the balloons which were mostly  filled with water.  These had followed the water’s currents around rocks and logs.  Some were quite far away from others, and some stay closer.  But they stayed either in or close to the river’s main current.  <br><br>
The father said of the mostly water-filled balloons, “These are like individuals who have a lot of love in their hearts, and remain true to the river’s currents.  The go around rocks and other obstacles with the current, and do not get mired down in the shallow waters near the edge of the river.  If we left them, they would continue down the river to destinations unknown.  <br><br>
Then he pulled out his pin, and punctured the balloon nearest the canoe. There was a large splash as the balloon’s water joined that of the river.  Again, the younger boy jumped at the suddenness of the commotion.  Bits of balloon drifted in the river.<br><br>
The father said, “What has this balloon contributed to the river?”  “All its water,” the boys replied.  “Yes,” the father said, “and although this balloon was smaller than the air-filled balloon, how much water did it contribute to the river, more or less than the air-filled balloon?”  “More,” the older replied, growing tired of the analogy.  The father replied, “Even the smallest water-filled balloon will contribute more water than the largest air-filled balloon.  Be aware, therefore, that there are some people who are filled only with hot air.  They will say things they don’t mean, and do things they say they won’t do.”  <br><br>
He turned to the older of the two boy in the stern of the canoe.  “You are going off to college soon, and you will meet some of these people.  Beware of them, as they cannot be trusted.”  He continued, talking to both of them, saying “The smallest water-filled balloon has more water to contribute to the river than the largest of the air-filled balloons.  The smallest good person has more love to contribute to the world than the largest hot-air-filled person.  For some reason, politicians or lawyers seem to be mostly filled with hot air.<br><br>
The father continued, “As the Lakota teach about feeding the White Wolf and feeding the Black Wolf inside us, we can influence the amount of Love or hate we let enter our bodies.  The types of thoughts, and our decisions, influence whether we become filled with Love or hate.  We can feed the White Wolf (Love) or the Black Wolf (hate).  But we can never be totally rig of either.  <br><br>
“But just as the pin punctured the balloon, we will die and shed this body.  The pin, if applied just right, can let out the air without shattering the body, or the knot can be untied.  But the balloon cannot do this itself.  That must happen from the outside.  <br><br>
“When we die, our life-force will be released to the universe.  Some people, of whom we know little, will contribute much to the good of this world.  Some people who are famous and known throughout the world, will contribute little to this life-force.<br><br>
“So to do religions have outside agents which intervene for us.  Jesus is one, as is Buddha with his enlightenment.  The important thing is to realize that outside help is needed to rid us entirely of the hate and evil we have been surrounded with.”  <br><br>
They found the last balloon, completely filled with water, just under the surface, broke it and freed its water to the river.  They then gathered up the remnants of the balloons, put them in the buckets, and paddled downstream.  As they were approaching their take-out point, the father said, almost as an afterthought, “In Vietnam, the United States was led mostly by men filled with hot air, at least at the top of the government.”<br>

